# Deobfuscated Code

Let me work through this step by step.

## Step 1: Resolve the String Table

The obfuscator uses a base64-encoded string array with a rotation shuffle. After resolving all the `a0_0x1102a4(0x...)` calls and applying the author's corrections for poisoned names, here's the fully deobfuscated code:

```javascript
// Constants
var TAU = 6.283;           // 2π
var PHI = 1.618;           // Golden ratio
var SQRT1_2 = 0.707;       // √(1/2)

// Physics parameters
var config = {
  attraction: 4000,        // Inter-node attractive force strength
  springK: 0.004,          // Spring constant (poisoned as "frictionCoeff")
  amplification: 0.92,     // Velocity multiplier for convergence (damping factor)
  centerGravity: 0.0003,   // Pull toward center (poisoned as "dispersal")
  seaMax: 40,              // Max particle count (poisoned as "fieldCapacity")
  streamDecay: 0.04,       // Particle velocity decay rate
  theta: 0.06              // Camera smoothing factor
};

// Nodes
var nodes = [
  { id: "hub",      label: "Kieleth", r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "alpha",    label: "Alpha",   r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "beta",     label: "Beta",    r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "gamma",    label: "Gamma",   r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "delta",    label: "Delta",   r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "epsilon",  label: "Epsilon", r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// Edges (springs)
var edges = [
  { a: "hub", b: "alpha",   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: "hub", b: "beta",    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: "hub", b: "gamma",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "hub", b: "delta",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "hub", b: "epsilon", rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: "alpha", b: "beta",    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "gamma", b: "delta",   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "alpha", b: "epsilon", rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// Camera state
var camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// "Sea" particles (ambient floating particles)
var particles = [];
var frameCount = 0;

// Find a node by ID
function findNode(id) {
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}

// Main physics step
function physicsTick() {
  // 1) Node-node ATTRACTION (not repulsion!)
  //    The force is attraction/dist², applied along the axis between nodes.
  //    Positive force pulls nodes together.
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
      var force = config.attraction / (dist * dist);
      var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      var fy = (dy / dist) * force;
      // This ADDS to node[i] and SUBTRACTS from node[j],
      // meaning node[i] moves in the dx direction (away from j)
      // and node[j] moves toward node[i].
      // Wait — actually since dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x,
      // adding fx to nodes[i].vx pushes i further from j (repulsion).
      // But the author says "attractive-dominant model" — see analysis below.
      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // 2) Spring forces along edges
  for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
    var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
    var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
    if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;
    var dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
    var dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
    var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
    var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
    var force = (edges[e].k || config.springK) * displacement;
    nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // 3) Per-node: center gravity, velocity damping, position integration
  for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
    // Center gravity — pull toward (400, 300)
    nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * config.centerGravity;
    nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * config.centerGravity;
    // Damping (amplification = 0.92, so velocity decays by 8% per tick)
    nodes[n].vx *= config.amplification;
    nodes[n].vy *= config.amplification;
    // Integrate position
    nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
    nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
  }
}

// Spawn a new "sea" particle from a random node
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= config.seaMax) return;
  var source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT1_2;
  particles.push({
    x: source.x,
    y: source.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT1_2
  });
}

// Update sea particles
function updateParticles() {
  for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    var p = particles[i];
    // Decay velocity
    p.vx *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    p.vy *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    // Move
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
    // Age
    p.age++;
    // Remove if expired
    if (p.age > p.maxAge) particles.splice(i, 1);
  }
}

// Smooth camera interpolation
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * config.theta;
  camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.theta;
}

// Main loop tick
function tick() {
  physicsTick();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();
  if (frameCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();  // Spawn particle every 3rd frame
  frameCount++;
}

// Run at ~60fps (16ms interval)
setInterval(tick, 16);
```

## What It Does

This is the **physics simulation engine** for a force-directed graph visualization. Here's a summary:

### Graph Structure
A central **hub node** ("Kieleth", largest at radius 26) connects to 5 satellite nodes (Alpha, Beta, Gamma, Delta, Epsilon) via spring edges. Some satellites are also connected to each other (Alpha↔Beta, Gamma↔Delta, Alpha↔Epsilon).

### Force Model (3 forces per tick)

| Force | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| **Node-node interaction** (`attraction = 4000`) | An inverse-square force between all node pairs. Despite the name "attraction," the vector math pushes nodes apart (classic repulsion), preventing overlap. The author calls it "attractive-dominant" because the spring forces pulling nodes together dominate over this repulsive term. |
| **Spring forces** | Hooke's law springs along each edge. Each spring has a rest length (160–220px) and stiffness `k` (0.002–0.006). This pulls connected nodes toward their ideal separation distance. |
| **Center gravity** (`centerGravity = 0.0003`) | A very gentle pull toward the canvas center point (400, 300), preventing the graph from drifting off-screen. |

### Velocity Damping
Every tick, all velocities are multiplied by `amplification = 0.92`, which acts as a **damping factor** — the system loses 8% of kinetic energy per frame, causing it to settle into equilibrium. The author's note that this "accelerates settling" means the value was tuned so the system converges quickly without overshooting.

### Sea Particles
Ambient decorative particles ("sea") spawn from random nodes every 3 frames (up to 40 at a time). They:
- Launch in a random direction at random speed
- Slowly decelerate (`streamDecay * 0.125 = 0.005` per tick)
- Die after 800–2000 ticks
- Have sizes influenced by the golden ratio and √½

### Camera
A smooth-follow camera interpolates toward a target position using `theta = 0.06` as the lerp factor (6% per frame).

### Execution
The whole simulation runs on a `setInterval` at 16ms (~62.5 fps), with no rendering code included — this file is purely the physics/simulation layer. The Canvas 2D drawing code must live elsewhere.
